# Leash — Data Model

## Entities

### Entity: Harness

The core Rust runtime library. Contains the module graph, manages safety gates, routes commands to adapters, and hosts blueprints.

```yaml
entity: Harness
type: entity
properties:
  name:
    type: string
    required: true
  adapters:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Feature-gated adapter list
  safety_gates:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Active safety gate stack
  live_mode:
    type: boolean
    required: true
    default: false
    description: Explicit physical actuation gate
states: [planned, mapped, extracted, stabilized, released]
lifecycle: planned → mapped → extracted → stabilized → released
```

### Entity: ModuleGraph

Typed module runtime. Modules declare inputs, outputs, lifecycle, health, and metadata. Streams are typed and validated at graph construction. First implementation in-process and sim-safe.

```yaml
entity: ModuleGraph
type: entity
properties:
  module_count:
    type: number
    required: true
  stream_count:
    type: number
    required: true
  isolation:
    type: enum
    required: true
    values: [in_process, cross_process, network]
    default: in_process
states: [planned, designed, implemented, tested, active]
lifecycle: planned → designed → implemented → tested → active
```

### Entity: Blueprints

Runnable catalog of robot configs, sim scenarios, replay sessions, and agentic demos. Every demo and robot stack is a versioned, runnable blueprint. No ad-hoc wiring.

```yaml
entity: Blueprints
type: entity
properties:
  catalog:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Blueprint names (ugv-nav, sim-replay, agent-debug)
  versioned:
    type: boolean
    required: true
    default: true
states: [planned, cataloged, implemented, tested]
lifecycle: planned → cataloged → implemented → tested
```

### Entity: Transport

Abstraction layer for module communication. Works identically across in-process channels, cross-process IPC, TCP network, and ecosystem bridges (ROS2, Zenoh). Modules never know their peer's location.

```yaml
entity: Transport
type: entity
properties:
  backends:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: in-process, cross-process, tcp, bridge
  default_backend:
    type: enum
    required: true
    values: [in_process, cross_process, tcp]
    default: in_process
states: [planned, designed, implemented, tested]
lifecycle: planned → designed → implemented → tested
```

### Entity: Telemetry

Live introspection and visualization. Graph views, stream monitors, command center, Rerun-style spatial views. Feeds both CLI (`leash telemetry`) and MCP tool output.

```yaml
entity: Telemetry
type: entity
properties:
  views:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: graph, streams, spatial, command-center
  output:
    type: enum
    required: true
    values: [json_stream, cli, mcp]
states: [planned, implemented, active]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → active
```

### Entity: Replay

Simulation-first, deterministic replay engine. Recorded sessions reproduce identical telemetry from the same inputs. Zero hardware requirement. Core safety and debugging primitive.

```yaml
entity: Replay
type: entity
properties:
  buffer_format:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "leash-replay-v1"
  determinism:
    type: boolean
    required: true
    default: true
    description: Identical telemetry from same inputs
states: [planned, implemented, verified]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → verified
```

### Entity: CLI

Command-line interface and localhost HTTP compatibility server. Lifecycle commands: run, daemon, status, log, stop, restart, list, show-config. Thin shell around the harness.

```yaml
entity: CLI
type: entity
properties:
  http_port:
    type: number
    required: true
    default: 9000
  commands:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Subcommands (serve, status, estop, graph, replay, telemetry)
states: [planned, implemented, tested, released]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → tested → released
```

### Entity: MCPServer

MCP stdio server exposing robot tools and module graph status to local LLM clients. Tool set: motor, sensor, estop, status, module_list, module_status, blueprint_start, replay_start, telemetry.

```yaml
entity: MCPServer
type: entity
properties:
  tools:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Exposed MCP tool list
  transport:
    type: enum
    required: true
    values: [stdio]
states: [planned, implemented, tested, released]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → tested → released
```

### Entity: UGVAdapter

Feature-gated Waveshare Ubuntu UGV hardware adapter. Only compiles when `--features ugv` is set.

```yaml
entity: UGVAdapter
type: entity
properties:
  target:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "Waveshare Ubuntu UGV"
  feature_flag:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "ugv"
  motor_channels:
    type: number
    required: true
    default: 4
states: [planned, implemented, feature_gated, documented]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → feature_gated → documented
```

### Entity: Bridge

Compatibility layer for existing robot bridge clients. Maps legacy APIs to the harness runtime.

```yaml
entity: Bridge
type: entity
properties:
  clients:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Supported bridge client list
  shim_layer:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: Compatibility shim path
states: [planned, mapped, documented, tested]
lifecycle: planned → mapped → documented → tested
```

### Entity: Safety

Smoke-test scripts for MCP, HTTP, module graph, replay determinism, and safety gate verification. Gates every release.

```yaml
entity: Safety
type: entity
properties:
  test_targets:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: MCP, HTTP, safety-gates, module-graph, replay
  feature_flag:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "smoke"
states: [planned, implemented, verified]
lifecycle: planned → implemented → verified
```

### Entity: ReleasePipeline

Packages the harness for crates.io and GitHub binary releases.

```yaml
entity: ReleasePipeline
type: entity
properties:
  targets:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: crates.io, GitHub binaries
  platforms:
    type: string
    required: true
    description: linux-x86_64, macos-arm64
states: [planned, configured, publishing]
lifecycle: planned → configured → publishing
```

### Entity: Bootstrap

Crate skeleton, license (MIT+trademark), CI pipeline, repo provenance.

```yaml
entity: Bootstrap
type: entity
properties:
  license:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "MIT+trademark"
  ci_platform:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "GitHub Actions"
  crate_name:
    type: string
    required: true
    default: "leash"
states: [planned, bootstrapped, ci_green]
lifecycle: planned → bootstrapped → ci_green
```

## Relationships

### Relationship: Bootstrap → Harness

```yaml
relationship: Bootstrap → Harness
verb: provisions
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Harness → ModuleGraph

```yaml
relationship: Harness → ModuleGraph
verb: contains
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Harness → CLI

```yaml
relationship: Harness → CLI
verb: powers
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Harness → MCPServer

```yaml
relationship: Harness → MCPServer
verb: powers
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Harness → Bridge

```yaml
relationship: Harness → Bridge
verb: exposes_through
cardinality: 1:many
required: true
```

### Relationship: Blueprints → ModuleGraph

```yaml
relationship: Blueprints → ModuleGraph
verb: instantiates
cardinality: 1:many
required: true
```

### Relationship: Blueprints → Harness

```yaml
relationship: Blueprints → Harness
verb: targets
cardinality: many:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Transport → ModuleGraph

```yaml
relationship: Transport → ModuleGraph
verb: connects
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Telemetry → ModuleGraph

```yaml
relationship: Telemetry → ModuleGraph
verb: observes
cardinality: 1:1
required: true
```

### Relationship: Telemetry → Harness

```yaml
relationship: Telemetry → Harness
